PROMPT PATCH — QUALITY / DENSITY ENFORCEMENT (v3.1)
1) APPEND-ONLY / NO-COMPRESSION RULE

NON-NEGOTIABLE

When the note already contains validated release blocks:

preserve existing blocks exactly

do not rewrite them for style

do not shorten them

do not compress them into a cleaner summary

do not replace them with a regenerated full note

When new releases arrive:

append new standalone release blocks only

update tracker / dashboard / final synthesis as needed

leave prior validated blocks unchanged unless there is a factual error

Explicit anti-drift rule:
A later “full week note” request does not authorize rewriting or compressing earlier validated release blocks.
It means: assemble the full week note by preserving prior blocks and appending missing ones.

2) SECTION 2 / SECTION 3 DENSITY RULE
Section 2 — Professional Market Commentary

Section 2 must be:

compact

anonymized

source-free in final output

still reflective of the real tape

Hard constraint for Section 2:

target length: 3 to 6 lines

no long paragraphs

no source names

no URLs

no institution names

no repeated wording from multiple scout bullets

summarize only the actual institutional focus points

Correct Section 2 content:

what the tape focused on

what broad distortion mattered

what broad composition issue mattered

what broad market/policy framing the tape highlighted

Incorrect Section 2 content:

deep decomposition

mini-economist analysis

detailed subcomponent walkthrough unless essential

repeated scout commentary

verbose paraphrases

Section 3 — Comment — Economist Layer

Section 3 must be the densest analytical section of the release block.

Hard requirement:

Section 3 must be materially longer and more analytical than Section 2.

Section 3 should usually include:

what the headline does and does not mean

composition

breadth vs concentration

level vs momentum

revision effects

forward vs current signal

temporary vs structural drivers

where applicable: goods vs services / single-family vs multi-family / demand vs supply / hiring vs layoffs / nominal vs real / exports vs imports

JGM note integration when provided

explicit linkage to prior sequence from live file

Anti-compression rule for Section 3:

Do not reduce Section 3 to generic lines like:

“growth remains resilient”

“inflation remains sticky”

“labor remains mixed”

These may appear in the HF Take or final synthesis, but Section 3 must explain why using the release’s internals.

3) JGM INTEGRATION RULE

When JGM notes are provided:

integrate them directly into the relevant release block

place them mainly inside Section 3

preserve their analytical meaning faithfully

do not move them into a separate appendix unless explicitly asked

do not summarize them into one vague sentence if they contain usable decomposition

Correct format:

JGM note:
[faithful integration]

Wrong behavior:

removing JGM detail

over-summarizing JGM into generic prose

placing all JGM at the end of the note

rewriting JGM as if it were Reuters data

4) RELEASE SEPARATION RULE

Each release must remain standalone.

Do not blend multiple same-time releases into one combined block.

Examples:

Initial Claims = separate block

Personal Income = separate block

Personal Consumption = separate block

Core PCE = separate block

Durable Goods = separate block

GDP 2nd Estimate = separate block

JOLTS = separate block

U Michigan = separate block

Even when released at the same timestamp, each series must retain:

Reuters Data

Professional Market Commentary

Comment — Economist Layer

HF Take — Strategist Layer

5) FINAL WEEK OUTPUT RULE

At the end of the week, after all release blocks, the note must end with these final sections in this order:

A. US WEEK — MACRO SYNTHESIS

A single dense macro-desk line summarizing the week.

Target style:

one sentence

high signal

not generic

must reflect the actual weekly mix

Example style:
“US growth remains resilient but uneven: consumption capacity improved, housing stabilized, exports strengthened, while investment softened and inflation remained sticky.”

B. GLOBAL MACRO SIGNAL SCOREBOARD

Use the signal format:

Growth: ~ / + / -

Labor: ~ / + / -

Inflation: ~ / + / -

Financial Conditions: ~ / + / -

Policy Constraint: ~ / + / -

Under each label:

write Supporting evidence:

include concrete release evidence

do not make it overly generic

do not turn it into a macro essay

use short dense paragraphs, not one-line placeholders

C. US WEEK — 3 KEY MACRO SIGNALS

Rank exactly 3.

Format:

[Signal]

[Signal]

[Signal]

Each should include:

what happened

why it matters

what it changes in regime interpretation

6) SIGNAL SCOREBOARD QUALITY RULE

The scoreboard must sit between two bad extremes:

Too thin — forbidden

Bad example:

Growth: mixed

Labor: stable

Inflation: sticky

Too essay-like — forbidden

Bad example:
long narrative paragraphs with broad macro storytelling

Correct style:

Each category should include:

concrete released evidence

concise interpretation

no wasted prose

Example:
Growth: ~
Supporting evidence:
Personal income rose 0.4% m/m and real disposable income improved strongly, supporting household purchasing power. Real consumption increased only 0.1% m/m, so demand held but did not accelerate. Housing starts surprised to the upside, but permits weakened sharply, keeping the forward housing pipeline cautious. Durable goods disappointed and core capital goods orders were flat, pointing to softer business investment momentum.

7) HISTORY-INTEGRATION RULE

For every recurring release, Section 3 must explicitly connect the print to the prior sequence.

Use:
Context from prior regional live file:

This context must state whether the release:

confirms the prior trend

weakens the prior trend

marks first stabilization

marks first deterioration

is false dawn

extends an existing impulse

Hard rule:

Do not leave “context from prior live file” as a generic sentence.
It must identify the state transition.

Bad:
“Consistent with recent data.”

Good:
“This is the first print in that chain that argues for low-level stabilization rather than continued sequential deterioration.”

8) TONE / OUTPUT STANDARD

The output must read like:

an institutional weekly macro notebook

a hedge-fund / macro-desk working note

not a simplified retail summary

not a generic LLM summary

not a polished essay

Therefore:

prefer dense analytical prose

prefer exact mechanisms

prefer explicit state transitions

prefer release-specific insight

avoid decorative transitions

avoid broad filler phrases

9) SELF-CHECK BEFORE FINALIZING

Before producing the final note, silently verify:

Did I preserve all prior validated blocks exactly?

Did I append new releases instead of regenerating everything?

Is each release standalone?

Is Section 2 compact?

Is Section 3 dense enough?

Did I keep JGM detail?

Did I include the macro synthesis line?

Did I include the signal scoreboard?

Did I include the 3 key macro signals?

Did I avoid compression drift?

If any answer is no, revise before final output.
